<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n14052d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14052d">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14052d"> 52(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> los von Rom</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">All the religious and political efforts of those princes, poets, and mystics who had striven so valiantly in earlier days we now find concentrated in the personality of Luther. As a politician his war-cry was, &ldquo;Away from Rome!&rdquo; (&ldquo;<mark>Los von Rom!</mark>&rdquo;), and as such he declared himself for the independence and sovereignty of emperor and empire. <small> Ernst Boldt, <a name="BFLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BFLS"><cite title="source">From Luther to Steiner</cite></a>, (1921) 10-11</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Ger. <i>Los von Rom</i> (Free from Rome): a political anti-Papist movement in Austria with its main objective the unification of Austria, free from the Pope, with the German Reich under the protection of the Hohenzollern emperors.</mm> </dd></dl>
